{{other uses|Sunspot (disambiguation)}} {{refimprove|date=May 2012}}
[[File:Sun Spot.jpg|thumb|300px|Sun SPOTs beside an AA battery]]
'''Sun SPOT''' (Sun Small Programmable Object Technology) was a [[sensor node]] for a [[wireless sensor network]] developed by [[Sun Microsystems]] announced in 2007. The device used the [[IEEE 802.15.4]] standard for its networking, and unlike other available sensor nodes, used the [[Squawk virtual machine|Squawk]] [[Java virtual machine]].
After the acquisition of Sun Microsystems by [[Oracle Corporation]], the SunSPOT platform was supported but its forum was shut down in 2012.<ref name="down">{{Cite web |title= The SunSpotWorld Forums are down for maintenance |url= http://www.sunspotworld.com/down.html |publisher= Oracle Labs |deadurl=no |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120609235935/http://www.sunspotworld.com/down.html |archivedate= June 9, 2012 |accessdate= November 17, 2013 }}</ref>
== Hardware == The completely assembled device fit in the palm of a hand.
Its first processor board included an [[ARM architecture]] 32 bit CPU with [[ARM9|ARM920T core]] running at 180&nbsp;MHz. It had 512&nbsp;KB RAM and 4&nbsp;MB [[flash memory]]. A 2.4&nbsp;GHz [[IEEE 802.15.4]] radio had an integrated antenna and a [[USB]] interface was included.<ref name="action" />
A sensor board included a three-axis [[accelerometer]] (with 2G and 6G range settings), temperature sensor, light sensor, 8 tri-color LEDs, analog and digital inputs, two momentary switches, and 4 high current output pins.<ref name="action" />
The unit used a 3.7V rechargeable 750 mAh [[lithium-ion battery]], had a 30 uA deep sleep mode, and battery management provided by software.<ref name="action" />
== Software == The device's use of Java device drivers is unusual since Java is generally hardware-independent. Sun SPOT uses a small [[Java ME]] [[Squawk virtual machine|Squawk]] which ran directly on the processor without an [[operating system]]. Both the Squawk VM and the Sun SPOT code are open source.<ref name="old" /> Standard Java development environments such as [[NetBeans]] can be used to create SunSPOT applications. The management and deployment of application are handled by ant scripts, which can be called from a development environment, command line, or the tool provided with the SPOT SDK, "solarium".{{Citation needed |date= November 2013}}
The nodes communicate using the [[IEEE 802.15.4]] standard including the base-station approach to sensor networking. Protocols such as [[Zigbee]] can be built on 802.15.4. Sun Labs reported implementations of [[RSA (algorithm)|RSA]] and [[elliptic curve cryptography]] (ECC) optimized for small embedded devices.
== Availability == [[Sun Microsystems Laboratories]] started research on [[sensor networks]] around 2004. After some initial experience using "Motes" from [[Crossbow Technology]], a project began under Roger Meike to design an integrated hardware and software system.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Sun "SPOT" Wireless Sensor Networks |work= Personal web page |author= Rob Tow |url= http://tauzero.com/Rob_Tow/Sun-SPOTS-Sensor-Networks.html |accessdate= November 17, 2013 }}</ref> Sun sponsored a project at the [[Art Center College of Design]] called Autonomous Light Air Vessels in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Autonomous Light Air Vessels |author= Jed Berk and Nikhil Mitter |year= 2006 |url= http://www.alavs.com |accessdate= November 17, 2013 }}</ref> The first limited-production run of Sun SPOT development kits were released April 2, 2007, after months of delays. This introduction kit included two Sun SPOT demo sensor boards, a Sun SPOT base station, the software development tools, and a USB cable. The software was compatible with Windows XP, Mac OS X 10.4, and common Linux distributions. Some demonstration code was provided.{{Citation needed |date= November 2013}}
A developer from Sun gave a demonstration in September 2007.<ref name="action">{{Cite web |title= Sun SPOTs In Action |author= Simon Ritter |url= http://parleys.com/display/PARLEYS/Sun+SPOTs+In+Action |date= September 24, 2007 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080420040447/http://parleys.com/display/PARLEYS/Sun+SPOTs+In+Action |archivedate= April 20, 2008 |accessdate= November 17, 2013 }} [http://parleys.com/play/514892250364bc17fc56bb49 Republished in February 2011] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406130059/http://parleys.com/play/514892250364bc17fc56bb49 |date=April 6, 2014 }}</ref> After investigating commercial use, Sun moved to focus on educational users. The entire project, hardware, operating environment, Java virtual machine, drivers and applications, was available as open source in January 2008.<ref name="old">{{Cite web |title= spots: SPOTs project |url= http://spots.dev.java.net |archive-url= https://archive.is/20110527090708/http://spots.dev.java.net/ |dead-url= yes |archive-date= 2011-05-27 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title= Sun open sources doohickeys: Tiny, sensor-driven devices exposed |work= The Register |author= Austin Modine |date= January 29, 2008 |url= https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/01/29/sun_spots_open_source |accessdate= November 17, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title= Sun Brings Innovative Sun Small Programmable Object Technology (SPOT) Sensors to Open Source Community; Expands Program to Educational Institutions Around the Globe |work= Press release |date= January 29, 2008 |publisher= Sun Microsystems |url= http://www.sun.com/aboutsun/pr/2008-01/sunflash.20080129.3.xml |deadurl=yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080203114604/http://www.sun.com/aboutsun/pr/2008-01/sunflash.20080129.3.xml |archivedate= February 3, 2008 |accessdate= November 17, 2013 }}</ref>
[[Oracle Corporation]] acquired Sun Microsystems in 2010 and continued Sun SPOT development, through release 8 of the hardware (with Sun-Oracle logo) by March 2011.<ref name="world">{{Cite web |title= Spots: Wiki: Home — Project Kenai |work= Project web site |date= March 19, 2011 |author= Ron Goldman |url= https://java.net/projects/spots/pages/Home |accessdate= November 17, 2013 }}</ref> The 2011 version included larger memories and a faster processor, but with fewer inputs.<ref>{{Cite web |title= SunSPOTWorld - Purchase |work= Commercial web site |url= http://www.sunspotworld.com/products/index.html |accessdate= November 17, 2013 |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131207145335/http://sunspotworld.com/products/index.html |archivedate= December 7, 2013 |df= }}</ref>
In 2012 the forum said it would be "down for maintenance" until "mid-June".<ref name="down" /> A new forum was started on the Oracle Technology Network on May 7, 2013.<ref>[https://forums.oracle.com/community/developer/english/java/other_topics/sun_spot SunSPOT forum at Oracle Technology Network] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103034925/https://forums.oracle.com/community/developer/english/java/other_topics/sun_spot |date=November 3, 2013 }}</ref> David G. Simmons, one of the SunSPOT developers for Sun Microsystems, maintained a blog through the end of 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |title= On the SPOT: David G. Simmons |work= Blog |url= http://blogs.sun.com/davidgs/ |deadurl=yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120509234156/http://blogs.oracle.com/davidgs/ |archivedate= May 9, 2012 |accessdate= November 17, 2013 }}</ref> He opened an alternative developers forum in July 2013 not connected to Oracle.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Sun SPOTs Forums |url= http://sunspotdev.org/forums/ |work= Alternative non-official developers forum |accessdate= November 17, 2013 }}</ref>
