'''Technology Aware Design''' ('''TAD''') is a [[research program]] that started in 2001 at [[imec]], [[Leuven]], [[Belgium]].<ref>[http://www.imec.be/tad IMEC's TAD program homepage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071005124511/http://www.imec.be/tad/ |date=2007-10-05 }}.</ref> It anticipates the end of the traditional "[[happy scaling]]" paradigm, where [[CMOS]] technology and CMOS design evolved on formally separate tracks, the interface between the two being [[standard cell]], or [[SPICE]] compact models (see [[transistor models]] for circuit design).{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}}

Today, both sides ([[design]] and [[technology]]) are confronted with the need to understand the other in order to overcome new scaling induced issues. The TAD program pursues analysis and solutions for these scaling induced problems.{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}}

